ck, Rome finds himself deep in a case which provides few answers.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Raquel Welch Frank Sinatra Lady in Cement.jpg|thumb|right|Sinatra and Welch]]\n* [[Frank Sinatra]] as Tony Rome\n* [[Raquel Welch]] as Kit Forrester\n* [[Dan Blocker]] as Waldo Gronski\n* [[Richard Conte]] as Lt. Dave Santini\n* [[Martin Gabel]] as Al Mungar\n* [[Richard Deacon (actor)|Richard Deacon]] as Arnie Sherwin\n* [[Lainie Kazan]] as Maria Baretto\n* [[Pat Henry (comedian)|Pat Henry]] as Rubin\n* [[Steve Peck]] as Paul Mungar (as Steven Peck)\n* [[Virginia Wood]] as Audrey\n* [[Frank Raiter]] as Danny Yale\n* [[Peter Hock]] as Frenchy\n* [[Alex Stevens (actor)|Alex Stevens]] as Shev\n* [[Christine Todd]] as Sandra Lomax\n* [[Mac Robbins]] as Sidney the organizer\n* [[Tommy Uhlar]] as The Kid, Tighe Santini\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a novel published in 1961 which the ''New York Times'' called \"ingenuous\".<ref>By, A. B. (1961, Jun 04). Criminals at large. New York Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/115449613</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of ''[[Tony Rome]]'', Aaron Rosenberg hired Marvin Albert to adapt ''Cement'' for Sinatra. The actor made it after ''The Detective''.<ref>Martin, B. (1967, Jun 05). 'Caper' for faye dunaway. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/155789349</ref> Raquel Welch's casting was announced in June 1967.<ref>Dorothy Manners:. (1967, Jun 30). Raquel welch to costar with sinatra. The Washington Post, Times Herald (1959-1973) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/143211118</ref>\n\n[[Sammy Davis Jr]] was to have appeared in the film as the charter boat captain.<ref>Sammy davis to costar with sinatra. (1968, Jan 06). The Washington Post, Times Herald (1959-1973) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/143516569</ref> However Sinatra fell ill and filming was postponed for four weeks. Davis was replaced by Pat Henry in the final film. <ref>Harford, M. (1968, Mar 06). 'SWEET CHARITY' ROLE. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/155915617</ref>\n\n[[Dan Blocker]] was given time away from ''Bonanza'' to play his part. The movie gave an early role to [[Lainie Kazan]].<ref>Rose, B. (1968, Jun 08). Miss kazan weighs love-career choice. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/155947940</ref>\n\nWelch later said she did not realise her character was an alcoholic until after filming wrapped. \"I'm watching this movie and I'm thinking, 'What the hell has she got on?' At one point, I had this epiphany: 'Oh, she's an alcoholic!' I didn't know that. How could I miss that?... I think I was just so enamoured with Frank Sinatra, you know. He's hypnotic.\"<ref>Wenn. (2017, April 10). Raquel Welch: 'I was awful in Sinatra film' Retrieved April 15, 2017, from [http://www.tv3.ie/xpose/article/entertainment-news/236582/Raquel-Welch-I-was-awful-in-Sinatra-film/ XPOS\u00c9.ie.]</ref>\n\nFilming started in March 1968. Before and during filming, Sinatra would perform at the Fontainebleau in Miami over a six-week period. Welch would go to watch him and found the experience so inspiring she determined to continue to perform to live audiences in her career.<ref>By, G. C. (1982, May 30). Raquel welch: 'I like a character with backbone'. New York Times (1923-Current File) Retrieved from https://search.proquest.com/docview/121982606</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAccording to Fox records the film required $7,150,000 in rentals to break even and by 11 December 1970 had made $6,825,000 so made a loss to the studio.<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/foxthatgotawayt00silv/page/327 327]|title=The Fox that got away : the last days of the Zanuck dynasty at Twentieth Century-Fox|url=https://archive.org/details/foxthatgotawayt00silv|url-access=registration|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M|year=1988|publisher=L. Stuart}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOpening to mixed reviews, ''Lady in Cement'' is generally considered to be a middling sequel to ''Tony Rome''. Critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave [[Damn with faint praise|faint praise]] in a generally scathing review by commenting: \u201cIn the movie's few good scenes, Sinatra once again painfully reminds us what a controlled, effective actor he is.\u201d [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] noted that \u201cDan Blocker is excellent as a sympathetic heavy,\u201d whilst John Maloney liked the \u201cfresher script\u201d and \u201csharp direction.\u201d\n\n==Home media==\n''Lady on Cement'' was released on DVD on May 24, 2005 as part of a boxed set along with ''[[Tony Rome]]'' and ''[[The Detective (1968 film)|The Detective]]'', both also directed by Douglas. No bonus features were included.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of American films of 1968]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0063210|title=Lady in Cement}}\n* {{amg movie|28088}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=80651}}\n* {{AFI film|id=23660|title=Lady in Cement}}\n* [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19681203/REVIEWS/812030301/1023 Roger Ebert\u2019s Review]\n* [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117792413.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&p=0 Variety\u2019s Review]\n* [http://www.dvdtimes.co.uk/content.php?contentid=57693 Review of the DVD Release by DVD Times]\n\n{{Gordon Douglas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lady In Cement}}\n[[Category:1968 films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:1960s mystery films]]\n[[Category:1960s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American neo-noir films]]\n[[Category:American detective films]]\n[[Category:American comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on mystery novels]]\n[[Category:Films s